Here are some additional AWK parameters and features we didn't cover in this lab:

Common awk Command Options
-F (Field Separator):
Defines the character used to separate fields in your input. By default, awk uses whitespace.
Example: awk -F"," '{print $1}' file.csv (uses a comma as a separator).

-v (Assign Variable):
Allows you to assign a value to a variable before the script execution begins.
Example: awk -v name="Labby" '{print name, $0}' file.txt.

-f (Read Script from File):
Tells awk to read the script commands from a specific file rather than the command line.
Example: awk -f script.awk data.log.

-v (Wait, there's more!):
If you ever need to see the full list of options available on your specific system, you can always run this command in your terminal:

man awk
Or use the help flag:

awk --help
Pro Tip for AWK
Remember those built-in variables we touched on in the lab? They are also very powerful for logic:

NR: Keeps track of the current Number of Records (line number).
NF: Keeps track of the Number of Fields in the current line.
